# project-druzya — service architecture standard

All services target the same layered shape, modelled on the reference service
`search-performance`. New services start from `services/template/`.

## Layering

```
client → internal/app/api/<name>/        transport: 1 RPC = 1 file, proto<->domain mapping, error mapping
       → internal/<domain>/service/        thin orchestrator: Service interface, wires usecase handlers
       → internal/<domain>/usecase/command/<op>/   write op:  command.go (Command+Validate) + handler.go (New+Handle) + mocks/
         internal/<domain>/usecase/query/<op>/     read op:   query.go   (Query+Validate)   + handler.go (New+Handle) + mocks/
       → internal/<domain>/repository/      concrete Postgres/Redis behind a Store/port interface
       | internal/adapter/<vendor>/         external gRPC/HTTP clients (one per vendor) + mocks/
```

Per-domain folders: `model/` (+ `errors.go` sentinels), `repository/` (+ `store.go` port),
`service/`, `usecase/{command,query}/`. Add `dto/`, `enum/`, `converter/` when mapping
or typing grows. Cross-cutting: `internal/config/`, `internal/tools/`, background workers
under `internal/<worker>/` or `internal/services/`.

## Reference exemplars (copy these shapes)

- Query: `services/template/internal/example/usecase/query/get_item/`
- Command: `services/interview/internal/interview/usecase/command/submit_attempt/`
- Repository port: `services/billing/internal/billing/repository/store.go`

## Conventions

- **Consumer-side interfaces**: declare the narrow interface a handler needs in the
  handler package; the concrete repo/adapter satisfies it. Never depend on a concrete
  `*Repository` from the service/usecase layer.
- **Mocks**: `//go:generate go run github.com/vektra/mockery/v2@... --case=underscore --with-expecter`
  on each port; run `go generate ./...` after changing an interface.
- **Validation**: each `Command`/`Query` has a `Validate()`; missing/bad input wraps a
  sentinel (`ErrInvalidArgument`/`ErrInvalidInput`), mapped to gRPC `InvalidArgument`.
- **Errors**: wrap with `%w`; domain sentinels live in `model/errors.go` (shared by
  service + usecase to avoid import cycles); transport `mapServiceError` maps them to codes.
- **Transactions**: multi-write operations use the repository `WithTx(ctx, fn)` +
  context-aware connection (`conn(ctx)`); idempotency guards (outbox/processed_events)
  run inside the transaction (INSERT ... ON CONFLICT DO NOTHING RETURNING).
- **Quotas / external side effects**: gate (no consume) before work; consume after the
  durable write succeeds; compensate on later failure.
- **One RPC per transport file**; thin handlers (validate → call service → map error).
- **Typed enums, not raw strings**: finite domain values (status, type, mode, priority) use
  proto `enum` in `.proto`, typed aliases in `model/enums.go` (DB/API wire values as snake_case
  string constants), and `internal/app/api/<name>/proto_enums.go` for domain↔proto mapping.
  Do not expose bare `string` fields for closed sets in public API or domain models. Reference:
  `services/interview/internal/interview/model/enums.go`, `services/recommendation/internal/recommendation/model/enums.go`.
- English code/logs/comments; user commits manually; minimal diffs.

## Migration posture

Don't big-bang. Per service: fix correctness first, then add repository ports + mocks
+ tests, then extract the highest-complexity operations into `usecase/` packages.
Keep trivial CRUD reads inline — don't over-engineer.

## Build / verify (per service, from its root)

```bash
cd services/<name>
GOPROXY=https://proxy.golang.org,direct GOWORK=off go build ./...
GOPROXY=https://proxy.golang.org,direct GOWORK=off go test ./...
```

## Documentation

- `services/<name>/AGENTS.md` — source of truth per service; update with code changes.
- `docs/onboarding/README.md` — cross-service map for humans.
- `.cursor/rules/agents-md.mdc` — when agents must refresh docs.
- `docs/architecture/outbox-relay.md` — future message-bus relay design (polling is current default).
